## Dependency Anti-Patterns To Avoid

List anti-patterns relevant to dependency interpretation.

| ID                       | Anti-Pattern                                                           | Why It Is Harmful                                                                                                    | Corrective Principle                                                                                                |
| ------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| EVAL-DEP-ANTIPATTERN-001 | Treating an eval check as a dependency without deriving prerequisites. | It produces a requirement restatement instead of an actionable dependency inventory.                                   | Derive the behavior, technical condition, evidence, and operation needed to satisfy the check.                      |
| EVAL-DEP-ANTIPATTERN-002 | Treating implementation existence as dependency satisfaction.          | An artifact may exist while the eval requirement remains unmet.                                                      | Require source-traceable evidence and mark repository status Not Assessed unless explicitly evaluated.              |
| EVAL-DEP-ANTIPATTERN-003 | Omitting operational dependencies.                                     | Evals may fail or become unreliable because fixtures, generated reports, baselines, run procedures, or evidence practices are missing. | Extract executable process and maintenance prerequisites as first-class dependencies.                               |
| EVAL-DEP-ANTIPATTERN-004 | Hiding negative controls inside positive-path dependencies.            | False success can remain undetected.                                                                                 | Represent negative controls and safe-failure behavior separately.                                                   |
| EVAL-DEP-ANTIPATTERN-005 | Recreating dependency relationships as separate crosswalks.             | The same source, gate, evidence, and blocking relationships get repeated and drift across sections.                  | Capture relationships once in the dependency catalog; use shared and specialized sections only when they add value. |
| EVAL-DEP-ANTIPATTERN-006 | Inventing architecture from dependency analysis.                       | Dependency inventory becomes an implementation design rather than eval-derived requirement analysis.                 | Describe required technical conditions without prescribing implementation mechanisms unless the eval requires them. |
| EVAL-DEP-ANTIPATTERN-007 | Treating policy-mediated artifacts as dependencies.                    | It allows non-implementation artifacts to replace executable checks, generated evidence, runtime metadata, validation, or result aggregation. | Model only the deterministic execution-tied basis as dependencies; otherwise omit the source item from agent output. |
| EVAL-DEP-ANTIPATTERN-008 | Laundering semantic policy artifacts with implementation terms.         | Adding words such as implementation, metadata, generated, validation, or governance evidence can hide that the deliverable is still a policy artifact. | Require a concrete executable tie; if no eval path consumes, produces, compares, validates, persists, or queries the artifact, omit it. |

Add project-specific anti-patterns only if present in the eval specs.

